JD 39:

Key Responsibilities
1. Spend Baseline & Financial Modeling

Create and maintain accurate spend baselines across categories to enable credible savings and value measurement.

Build advanced Excel-based financial models to support sourcing decisions, savings scenarios, and long-term financial planning.

Interpret complex ERP and finance system data (SAP/Oracle) to extract actionable financial insights.

Translate raw spend and contract data into structured financial views for category decision-making.

2. Savings Calculation, Validation & Governance

Design and apply standardized savings calculation logic to distinguish clearly between cost reduction, cost avoidance, and value creation.

Establish savings validation methodologies aligned with finance, audit, and enterprise governance standards.

Perform savings validation and sign-off, ensuring only finance-approved benefits are recognized.

Conduct variance and leakage analysis to identify gaps between planned and realized savings.

Resolve disputes related to savings claims through data-backed analysis and structured escalation.

3. Budget, Forecasting & P&L Impact

Perform budget vs actual analysis to track financial performance at category and portfolio levels.

Assess and quantify P&L impact of procurement and category initiatives, ensuring alignment with financial plans.

Support long-term financial planning by embedding validated savings into forecasts and budgets.

Apply ROI and NPV analysis to evaluate sourcing initiatives, investments, and transformation programs.

4. Portfolio-Level Value Tracking

Lead portfolio-level value tracking, consolidating savings, cost optimization, and value levers across categories and regions.

Develop enterprise value realization models to track benefits beyond cost (margin, cash, risk).

Build and maintain finance dashboards and reporting dashboards using Power BI/Tableau for leadership visibility.

Ensure consistent value tracking methodologies across geographies and business units.

5. Financial Governance, Audit & Compliance

Design and implement financial governance frameworks for procurement and category value management.

Maintain audit-ready documentation to support internal audits, SOX requirements, and external reviews.

Ensure compliance with audit & SOX readiness standards, including documentation, traceability, and controls.

Define and enforce policies related to savings recognition, value tracking, and financial reporting.

6. Executive & Stakeholder Decision Support

Provide executive decision support through clear, concise, and data-driven financial insights.

Prepare executive reporting for senior leadership, steering committees, and C-suite forums.

Influence stakeholders with an enterprise P&L ownership mindset, balancing growth, cost, and risk.

Act as a trusted finance partner to procurement, category, and business leaders across regions.

7. Enterprise Transformation & Leadership

Drive procurement value transformation initiatives by embedding financial rigor into sourcing and category strategies.

Establish cross-region financial governance, ensuring consistency in value measurement and reporting.

Demonstrate leadership through structured problem-solving, stakeholder management, and C-suite influence.

Foster collaboration while maintaining high standards of accuracy, transparency, and accountability.

